Generative AI (GenAI) tools are increasingly woven into programming education, yet most studies are short-term and disconnected from coursework. To fill this gap, this work examines MerryQuery, a GenAI-powered assistant that grounds answers in instructor-curated materials, provides inline citations, offers scaffolded, step-by-step responses, and enables instructors to control response granularity and monitor student chat. MerryQuery was embedded across the weekly labs in an introductory MATLAB course, enrolling 313 non-CS majors. The mixed-methods analysis of the end-of-semester survey, and queries from representative early- and late-semester labs revealed that students had broadly positive perceptions and valued scaffolded guidance with citations, and queries were dominated by coding help. The study provides evidence of GenAI integration at scale, giving researchers and educators concrete insights for incorporating such tools into the classrooms.